li < ri <= 105\nAll the given intervals are unique.\n\n\n\n### Format: You will use the following starter code to write the solution to the problem and enclose your code within delimiters.\n```python\nclass Solution:\n    def removeCoveredIntervals(self, intervals: List[List[int]]) -> int:\n        \n```\n\n### Answer: (use the provided format with backticks)\n", "response": "```python\nfrom typing import List\n\nclass Solution:\n    def removeCoveredIntervals(self, intervals: List[List[int]]) -> int:\n        # Sort intervals by starting point. If two intervals have the same starting point, sort by ending point in descending order.\n        intervals.sort(key=lambda x: (x[0], -x[1]))\n        \n        # Initialize the end of the previous interval\n        prev_end = -1\n        count = 0\n        \n        for start, end in intervals:\n            # If the current interval is not covered by the previous one\n            if end > prev_end:\n                count += 1\n                prev_end = end\n        \n        return count\n```\n\n### Explanation:\n1. **Sorting**: The intervals are sorted by their starting points. If two intervals have the same starting point, they are sorted by their ending points in descending order. This ensures that if one interval starts where another starts, the longer interval comes first.\n2. **Tracking**: We keep track of the end of the last interval that was not covered (`prev_end`).\n3. **Counting**: For each interval, if its end is greater than `prev_end`, it means the current interval is not covered by the previous interval. We increment the count and update `prev_end` to the current interval's end.\n4. **Result**: The count at the end of the loop is the number of intervals that are not covered by any other interval.", "estimated_date": 1575763200000}